context: The undergraduates have a number of traditions: Painting The Rock (originally a fountain donated by the Class of 1902) is a way to advertise, for example, campus organizations, events in Greek life, student groups, and university-wide events. Dance Marathon, a 30-hour philanthropic event, has raised <a0_0>more than <b5_0>13 million dollars<b5_0/><a0_0/> in its history for various children's charities. Primal Scream is held at 9 p.m. on the Sunday before finals week every quarter; students lean out of windows or gather in courtyards and <a1_0><b6_0>scream<b6_0/><a1_0/>. Armadillo Day, or, more popularly, <a2_0>Dillo Day<a2_0/>, a day of music and food, is held on Northwestern's Lakefill every Spring <a3_0>on the <b7_0>weekend after Memorial Day<b7_0/><a3_0/>. And in one of the University's newer traditions, every year during freshman orientation, known as <a4_0><b8_0>Wildcat Welcome<b8_0/><a4_0/>, freshmen and transfer students pass through Weber Arch to the loud huzzahs of upperclassmen and the music of the University Marching Band.
